Simulation Scenario A: No bias anticipated





Cohort Description

The results in this summary are based on a simulated cohort of n = 99,649 50 year old individuals who were followed for up to 45 years with assessments for dementia status every five years. Dementia incidence rate = _____.

You have a single incidence rate in your draft, but we have different incidence rates because we have a much longer study period (50 years instead of 10). Do we want this to be a table of incidence rates?

Cumulative incidence of mortality during the study = NA%.

I calculated this as the proportion of dead people over the study period… is this right?

In this summary, we consider the scenario in which sex had no effect on development of dementia, but female sex decreased mortality risk

Do we want a table for this as well since the HRs change so much over the 50 year period?.

In our simulations, results that reject the null hypothesis that sex has no effect on dementia incidence (HR=1.00) are wrong.

Matching European Survival Data

We used dementia incidence rate data from the EURODEM studies so we needed to switch from US to European survival data. We found cohort life tables on UC Berkeley’s repository: https://www.mortality.org/. Pulling data for the countries included in the EURODEM study, we plotted hazard ratios and decided that the Netherlands data provided a nice middle ground in the 50+ age group.

Comparing Hazard Ratios

Lambda values

We were able to solve for the \(\lambda\) values in our survival model so that conditional probabilities of survival in our simulated data closely matched those calculated from the Netherlands life tables:
